  "footnotes": [
    "Aboriginal Australians are among the oldest continuous cultures on Earth, with evidence of habitation dating to at least 65,000 years ago. At the time of British colonisation in 1788 there were approximately 500 distinct language groups with populations estimated between 300,000 and 1,000,000. The frontier wars and disease epidemics of the colonial period caused catastrophic population collapse.",
    "Treaty of Waitangi (1840): signed between the British Crown and Māori chiefs, it remains New Zealand's founding document. The Māori-language and English versions differ significantly on questions of sovereignty (kāwanatanga) versus tino rangatiratanga (chieftainship), a tension that continues to shape New Zealand constitutional law.",
    "Tongan Empire (Tuʻi Tonga, c. 950–1500): the pre-eminent maritime polity of Polynesia, controlling trade and tribute networks across Fiji, Sāmoa, Tuvalu, and parts of Micronesia. The Tuʻi Tonga line remained a sacred chieftaincy even after political power shifted to the Tuʻi Kanokupolu dynasty.",
    "Kokoda Track Campaign (1942): Australian and Papuan forces halted the Japanese advance across the Owen Stanley Range in one of the most gruelling land campaigns of WWII; it is commemorated as a defining moment in Australian national identity alongside Gallipoli.",
    "Pacific Islands Trust Territory (1947–1994): the United States administered the former Japanese South Seas Mandate as the only UN Strategic Trust Territory, giving the US broad military rights. Nuclear testing was conducted in the Marshall Islands (Bikini and Enewetak atolls), displacing communities and causing lasting radiological contamination.",
    "Kingdom of Hawaiʻi (1795–1893): unified by Kamehameha I through conquest and diplomacy; the kingdom maintained diplomatic relations with major world powers and had a written constitution. It was overthrown in 1893 by a group of American businessmen backed by US Marines; the US government formally apologized for the overthrow in 1993 (Public Law 103-150).",
    "Fiji coups (1987, 2000, 2006): Fiji has experienced four coups since independence, largely driven by ethnic tensions between indigenous Fijians and Indo-Fijians (descendants of indentured laborers brought by the British). The country was suspended from the Commonwealth multiple times and returned to democratic elections in 2014.",
    "Nauru (1968): the world's smallest island republic, Nauru was one of the wealthiest nations per capita in the 1970s–1980s due to phosphate mining. Near-total depletion of phosphate reserves by the 1990s caused economic collapse; Nauru has since operated an Australian immigration detention centre as a major revenue source."
  ]
